zation. Stakeholders in these often emotionally and politically charged debates have arrived at what is potentially a solution that can satisfy all parties in the equation. Heritage covenants are a complex legal instrument involving the sale or donation of a heritage interest to a not-for-profit organization or government agency. In an unprecedented initiative, the Calgary Civic Trust, in the year 2000, brought together experts and leaders in heritage covenants from Canada, Great Britain, and the United States to discuss the future of this unique preservation instrument. This book is a result of the proceedings and focuses specifically on this sophisticated aspect of heritage preservation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCovenants (Law)vCongresses. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionvCongresses. 0aHistoric preservationvCongresses. 0aHistoric preservationzAlbertavCongresses. 7aARCHITECTURE / Historic Preservation / General.2bisacsh1 aButler, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenhez, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiscussion, Panel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdmondson, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnglish, Anne E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFranklin, Doug, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaskell, Kimberly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJennings, Sally, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcMordie, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula